countries.trigger: UK Government
countries.message: UK Government said: As part of the Counter Terrorism Command of the United Kingdom, the Internet Referral Unit (CTIRU) works in cooperation with industry and private sector companies globally to remove illegal online content that breaches the UK's terrorism provisions. We search for online content that is illegal under UK law that may be described as material that encourages, promotes or glorifies terrorist acts or which otherwise incites or assists others to participate in such acts. The types of content most often removed usually breach Sections 57 or 58 Terrorism Act 2000 or Sections 1 or 2 Terrorism Act 2006.

specials.message: In our assessment, the content remits to a manifesto, statement, and/or document either authored by a violent right-wing extremist or endorsed by them – in this case Brenton Tarrant’s “The Great Replacement” manifesto on the Christchurch attack 2019. The content promotes violence by presenting extremist ideologies and calling for violent/terrorist actions against the public. Such content might contribute to the radicalisation or commitment of violent crime of others in the online audience.

countries.message: UK Government said: As part of the Counter Terrorism Command of the United Kingdom, the Internet Referral Unit (CTIRU) works in cooperation with industry and private sector companies globally to remove illegal online content that breaches the UK's terrorism provisions. We search for online content that is illegal under UK law that may be described as material that encourages, promotes or glorifies terrorist acts or which otherwise incites or assists others to participate in such acts. The types of content most often removed usually breach Sections 57 or 58 Terrorism Act 2000 or Sections 1 or 2 Terrorism Act 2006.

The types of content most often removed usually breach Sections 57 or 58 Terrorism Act 2000 or Sections 1 or 2 Terrorism Act 2006.

Such content might contribute to the radicalisation or commitment of violent crime of others in the online audience.

countries.message: UK Government said: As part of the Counter Terrorism Command of the United Kingdom, the Internet Referral Unit (CTIRU) works in cooperation with industry and private sector companies globally to remove illegal online content that breaches the UK's terrorism provisions. We search for online content that is illegal under UK law that may be described as material that encourages, promotes or glorifies terrorist acts or which otherwise incites or assists others to participate in such acts. The types of content most often removed usually breach Sections 57 or 58 Terrorism Act 2000 or Sections 1 or 2 Terrorism Act 2006.

The types of content most often removed usually breach Sections 57 or 58 Terrorism Act 2000 or Sections 1 or 2 Terrorism Act 2006.

Such content might contribute to the radicalisation or commitment of violent crime of others in the online audience.

Such content might contribute to the radicalisation or commitment of violent crime of others in the online audience.
